						               													<description>In &amp;#231;&amp;#143;&amp;#160;&amp;#233;&amp;#156;&amp;#138;&amp;#231;&amp;#165;&amp;#173;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#229;&amp;#164;&amp;#156; (Tama Tamamatsuri No Yoru), roughly Night of the Pearl Festival, the players are buying and selling gems through a mancala mechanism.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player has a board divided into six sections, one for each of the colors of gems.  On their turn, a player choose all of the cubes in one section, picks them up, and distributes them as in mancala.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The color of the space where the last cube is placed and the number of cubes there determines the actions a player may take.  Specifically, the color of gem they can buy or sell and the maximum number they can buy or sell.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;After the distribution occurs, a market adjustment card is triggered from a face up pool which likely adjusts the value of a single colored gem up one, but may trigger a more volatile move.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends after a number of times through an event deck or when a player has accumulated a certain amount of money.  The players each get the same number of turns and the one with the most money wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
